      <h4>&#x1f517; Cross-References (Treasury of Scripture Knowledge)</h4>
      <a href="../interlinear/hos-2.html">Hos 2 9</a> <a href="../interlinear/lev-26.html">Lev 26 19</a> <a href="../interlinear/jer-14.html">Jer 14 1-Jer 14 6</a> <a href="../interlinear/1ki-17.html">1Kgs 17 1</a> <a href="../interlinear/deu-28.html">Deut 28 23-Deut 28 24</a> <a href="../interlinear/1ki-8.html">1Kgs 8 35</a> <a href="../interlinear/jol-1.html">Joel 1 18-Joel 1 20</a> 
    </div>
    <div class="tn-note">
      <strong>&#x1f4dd; Cultural Note:</strong> Yahweh is speaking as if the **heavens** and the **earth** were living things that could actively withhold **dew** and **produce** from the Judeans. If it would be helpful in your language, you could state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [there is no dew from the heavens above you and there is no produce from the earth]
    </div>
    <div class="tn-note">
      <strong>&#x1f4dd; Cultural Note:</strong> Yahweh is speaking as if **dew** fell from the **heavens**, that is, from the sky. He means implicitly that not only has rain not been falling from the sky, dew has not even been forming on the ground overnight. You could indicate that in your translation if it would be helpful to your readers. Alternate translation: [not only has it not been raining, dew has not even been forming,]
